{"type":"text","timestamp":1773433374180,"sessionID":"ses_31723c478ffe7uxAauRAAXY9ho","part":{"id":"prt_ce8dd94a4001WAqJAc4Zl6PJeZ","sessionID":"ses_31723c478ffe7uxAauRAAXY9ho","messageID":"msg_ce8dd8c02001F3l23uZUdmJZ4M","type":"text","text":"OK, that's the `ensureTasksFile` function - it has `console.error` and `console.log` but that's outside the archive command scope and happens before any command runs. That's a separate issue.\n\nLet me look at the code once more very carefully. Looking at `archive.ts` lines 48-68:\n\n```typescript\nif (opts.featureId) {\n    // Archive a specific feature\n    const idx = data.tasks.findIndex((f: Feature) => f.id === opts.featureId);\n    if (idx === -1) {\n      // Check if already in archive\n      if (data.archive.find((f) => f.id === opts.featureId)) {\n        outputMessage(fmt, `Task \"${opts.featureId}\" is already in the archive.`, {\n          already_archived: true,\n          id: opts.featureId,\n        });\n        return;\n      }\n      outputError(fmt, `Task \"${opts.featureId}\" not found.`);\n      return;\n    }\n    toArchive = [data.tasks[idx]];\n```\n\nWait, actually — I see something. `data.archive` could be null if `loadFeatures` doesn't find any archive. Let me look at `loadFeatures` again:\n\n```typescript\nexport function loadFeatures(...): FeaturesFile {\n  const tasksData = loadTasks(projectRoot, config);\n  const archiveData = loadArchive(projectRoot, config);\n  return {\n    ...tasksData,\n    archive: archiveData.tasks,\n  };\n}\n```\n\nThat should always return an array. But then on line 42-44:\n```typescript\nif (!data.archive) {\n    data.archive = [];\n}\n```\n\nThis is redundant but not an error.\n\nLet me think about this differently. Maybe the bug is more subtle. Maybe the actual problem is that when `loadFeatures` throws (for example, if YAML parsing fails or there's a filesystem error), the error would be an unhandled exception with a plain text stack trace instead of a JSON error response. Or maybe `data.tasks` might be null/undefined from `loadFeatures`, and trying to call `.findIndex` on it could throw.\n\nActually, let me look at what happens with `data.tasks`. In `loadTasksFromStore`, it always returns `{ ...meta, tasks: [] }` if no tasks exist. So `data.tasks` should always be an array.\n\nLet me try another approach - check if there's a try/catch pattern that other commands use but archive doesn't:","time":{"start":1773433374179,"end":1773433374179}}}
