{"type":"text","timestamp":1773433387235,"sessionID":"ses_31723c478ffe7uxAauRAAXY9ho","part":{"id":"prt_ce8ddce0c001QWHAfUVJwoWmVf","sessionID":"ses_31723c478ffe7uxAauRAAXY9ho","messageID":"msg_ce8ddc669001UyrUw3P1yCT46T","type":"text","text":"OK, so none of the task commands use `console.error` or try/catch. They all rely on the `outputError` helper. Archive.ts also uses `outputError` for its error path on line 60.\n\nWait, let me look at this from another angle. The task description says \"may have code paths that bypass it (e.g. early returns with console.error)\". Perhaps the current code IS correct for the specific error case mentioned (\"nonexistent task\") but there might be OTHER error cases that should be covered. Let me think about what could go wrong:\n\n1. **Archiving a task that is not done/cancelled** - when providing a specific task ID, the code archives it regardless of status. This could be considered a \"feature\", but if we want to restrict archiving to only done/cancelled tasks, we'd need a new error path.\n\nActually, let me re-read the task description once more:\n\n> `woco tasks archive nonexistent --output json` outputs plain text instead of JSON error. The error path needs to use outputError() from src/lib/output.ts. Check src/commands/tasks/archive.ts — it already imports outputError but may have code paths that bypass it (e.g. early returns with console.error). All error paths must go through outputError(fmt, message) so JSON consumers get structured error responses.\n\nLet me look at this from the `index.ts` side — the routing code for archive might have its own error handling:","time":{"start":1773433387222,"end":1773433387222}}}
